      "side": 1,
      "message": "I patched this CL in and tried a few quick hacks with interesting results.\n\nRunning skottie-sphere-controls.json normally I measured around 57ms frametimes in viewer.  Then forcing fancy lighting, around 73ms (1.28x).  Then switching all uniforms to splats in SkRuntimeEffect.cpp,\n\n              //uniform.push_back(p-\u003euniform32(uniforms-\u003epush(bits)).id);\n              uniform.push_back(p-\u003esplat(bits).id);\n\nNot as big a change as you\u0027d hope, around 68ms.\n\nI had hoped we\u0027d be able to constant-propagate away the fancy lighting if we know the values as constants, but I think I may be being stymied by skvm\u0027s reticence to fold 0.0*x into 0.0?  Adding in that not-quite legal optimization to skvm::Builder::mul_f32(),\n\n          if (this-\u003eisImm(x.id, 0.0f) || this-\u003eisImm(y.id, 0.0f)) { return splat(0.0f); }\n\nWe get down right where we want to be, 57ms!\n\nSo, two ideas to ponder:\n   - a flag to makeColorFilter() and makeShader() to bake in (some? all?)\n     uniforms as constants, maybe in SkRuntimeEffects::Options?\n   - give skvm a `F32 fast_mul(F32,F32)` that\u0027s allowed to assume 0*x\u003d\u003d0,\n     or maybe a Builder setting (seems dangerous)?",
